<p><strong>Dash</strong> is an <a title="Open source" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open_source">open source</a> <a title="Cryptocurrency" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptocurrency">cryptocurrency</a>. It is an <a class="mw-redirect" title="Altcoin" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Altcoin">altcoin</a> that was <a title="Fork (software development)" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fork_(software_development)">forked</a> from the <a title="Bitcoin" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitcoin">Bitcoin</a> protocol. It is also a <a title="Decentralized autonomous organization" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decentralized_autonomous_organization">decentralized autonomous organization</a> (DAO) run by a subset of its users, which are called "masternodes".</p>
<h2><span id="Design_and_governance" class="mw-headline">Design and governance</span></h2>
<p>Dash was designed to allow transactions quickly and to have a swift governance structure in order to overcome shortfalls in <a title="Bitcoin" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitcoin">Bitcoin</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Fortune_4-2" class="reference"></sup></p>
<h3><span id="Governance" class="mw-headline">Governance</span></h3>
<p>Governance is handled through a form of <a title="Decentralized autonomous organization" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decentralized_autonomous_organization">decentralized autonomous organization</a> in which decisions are made on a <a title="Blockchain" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blockchain">blockchain</a> via masternodes. Masternodes perform standard <a title="Node (networking)" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Node_(networking)">node</a> functions like hosting a copy of the blockchain, relaying messages, and validating transactions on the network, and in addition act as shareholders, voting on proposals for improving Dash's ecosystem. Along with masternodes, the system includes standard nodes and <a title="Bitcoin network" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitcoin_network#Mining">miners</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-fintech_2-1" class="reference"></sup></p>
<p>Running a masternode requires ownership of 1000 Dash. Masternodes are also required to have a static IP address and meet minimum requirements for CPU, RAM, disk space and network bandwidth.</p>
<p>A proof of service protocol ensures that masternodes have the most current blockchain protocol and are online.<sup id="cite_ref-Prusty_11-2" class="reference"></sup></p>
<p>The system's decentralization has been criticized due to a mishap, which allowed too many coins to be distributed at release. This concentrated the wealth to a small group, giving them disproportionate power in decisions over the currency&rsquo;s future.</p>
<h3><span id="Consensus" class="mw-headline">Consensus</span></h3>
<p><span id="X11" class="anchor"></span> As of 2018 coins were mined using a <a title="Proof of work" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proof_of_work">proof of work</a> algorithm with a <a title="Hash function" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hash_function">hash function</a> called "X11", with eleven rounds of hashing, and the average time to mine a coin was around two and a half minutes.<sup id="cite_ref-fintech_2-2" class="reference"></sup></p>
<h3><span id="Transactions" class="mw-headline">Transactions</span></h3>
<p>Masternodes provide two additional kinds of transactions. "InstantSend" bypasses mining and instead requires a consensus of masternodes to validate a transaction, speeding transactions. "PrivateSend" is intended to give users optional consumer-grade privacy; it mixes participating users' unspent Dash before executing a transaction.</p>

<p style="text-align: left;">Dash is a next generation, p2p payments network and cryptocurrency where transactions are recorded on the blockchain: a decentralized, distributed, public ledger. It provides users with a digital currency that is secure, portable, and fungible.</p>
